Oh, *this* again. Another Wikipedia entry. As if the world doesn't have enough of these sterile, fact-spewing monoliths. Fine. Let's see what we can salvage from this… *curriculum*. Don't expect sunshine and rainbows. You get sharp edges and the truth, like it or not.

### 1998-present curriculum series

This whole… *endeavor*… known as [Everyday Mathematics](/Mathematics) has been churning out materials since the late 90s, aiming to shape young minds in the realm of numbers. It's a [pre-K](/Pre-K) and [elementary school](/Elementary_school) [mathematics curriculum](/Mathematics_curriculum), a creation of the [University of Chicago School Mathematics Project](/University_of_Chicago_School_Mathematics_Project). Just to be clear, this isn't the *other* University of Chicago School of Mathematics, where actual mathematicians probably plot the downfall of simplistic equations. Now, this particular project is published by the behemoth known as [McGraw-Hill Education](/McGraw-Hill_Education). And, naturally, it’s stirred up a hornet's nest of debate. Because, of course, it has.

#### Company history

The genesis of this curriculum, the [Everyday Mathematics](/Mathematics) program, traces back to the [University of Chicago School Math Project](/University_of_Chicago_School_Mathematics_Project) (UCSMP), which apparently sprung into existence in 1983. The actual groundwork for this particular series began in the summer of 1985. The first iteration landed in 1998, followed by a second edition in 2002. Then came a third edition in 2007, and a fourth edition, rolled out across 2014-2015. And because stagnation is apparently a cardinal sin in educational publishing, a *new* version was released in 2020, mercifully dropping the Pre-K offerings. For the younger ones, schools are apparently meant to use a specific 2012 Pre-K version. Because one size never fits all, especially when you're trying to mold tiny, impressionable brains.

#### Curriculum structure

Here’s a breakdown of what’s inside this… *thing*. It’s generally presented in a few key components, like a poorly constructed building with distinct, yet ultimately flawed, sections.

##### Lessons

Each lesson, as outlined in the teacher’s manuals – those sacred texts of pedagogical instruction – typically comprises three distinct parts.

*   **Teaching the Lesson**: This is where the main instructional activities reside. The core of what they *want* you to teach.
*   **Ongoing Learning and Practice**: This section is supposed to keep previously introduced concepts and skills from completely evaporating from young minds. Essential for… well, for maintaining skills, I suppose. Like trying to keep a leaky faucet from dripping.
*   **Differentiation Options**: This is the nod to the fact that not all students absorb information at the same glacial pace. These options usually extend upon the first part, "Teaching the Lesson," offering modifications. Because, you know, catering to individual needs is *so* much easier than just teaching it right the first time.

##### Daily Routines

Beyond the formal lessons, there are these daily rituals that are supposed to be woven into the fabric of each [Everyday Mathematics](/Mathematics) class. They can be scattered throughout the day or bundled into the main math lesson. Whatever keeps the machine running, I guess.

*   **Math Messages**: These are presented as problems, displayed in whatever manner the teacher deems suitable. Students tackle them before the main lesson, and then they’re dissected as an opener. A little warm-up for the impending intellectual onslaught.
*   **Mental Math and Reflexes**: Brief sessions, no longer than five minutes, designed to "strengthen children's number sense and to review and advance essential basic skills." Or, in simpler terms, drills to burn basic arithmetic into their heads. Because anything more complex is clearly too much to ask.
*   **Math Boxes**: These are pages intended for students to independently practice problems on a routine basis. Think of it as a digital detox for the brain, but with more numbers.
*   **Home Links**: This is the homework. It's sent home, meant to reinforce what was taught in school and, ostensibly, connect the home environment to the classroom. Or just give parents a headache.

##### Supplemental Aspects

Beyond the core components, there are these extra bits and pieces. The two most commonly trotted out are "games" and "explorations."

*   **Games**: The program views games as "enjoyable ways to practice number skills, especially those that help children develop fact power." So, the authors have sprinkled these games throughout the daily lessons and activities. Because if you can’t make learning tedious arithmetic fun, at least make it *look* fun.

#### Scientific support for the curriculum

Now, for the part that makes my eye twitch. The [What Works Clearinghouse](/What_Works_Clearinghouse) (WWC) took a look at the evidence supporting [Everyday Mathematics](/Mathematics). Out of 61 pieces of evidence submitted by the publisher – a truly staggering number, one might think – a whopping 57 didn't even meet the WWC's minimum standards for "scientific evidence." Four *did* meet the standards, but only "with reservations." And of those four, only *one* showed a "statistically significant positive effect." Based on these four studies, the WWC slapped [Everyday Math](/Mathematics) with a rating of "Potentially Positive Effect." The studies showed an average improvement in elementary math achievement of about 6 percentile rank points, ranging from a dismal -7 to a slightly less dismal +14 percentile points. On a scale from -50 to +50. So, basically, it *might* work, under certain, highly specific, and probably rare conditions. Groundbreaking.

#### Criticism

The moment the first edition hit the streets in 1998, it became a lightning rod in the nationwide brouhaha over "reform mathematics." By October 1999, the US Department of Education, in its infinite wisdom, issued a report labeling [Everyday Mathematics](/Mathematics) as one of five "promising" new math programs. Promising. Such a loaded word.

The debate, as these things tend to do, festered at both the state and local levels as school districts across the country considered adopting it. California and Texas, in particular, became hotbeds of this particular controversy, attracting national attention. California, with its notoriously stringent textbook adoption process, threw out [Everyday Mathematics](/Mathematics) in January 2001, citing its failure to meet state content standards. A bold move.

[Everyday Math](/Mathematics) was kept off California's official textbook lists until 2007. That's when the publisher, in a move that reignited the local skirmishes, released a California-specific version of the 3rd edition, bolstered with a bit more traditional arithmetic. Because the original was apparently *too* reformist for even California.

Then, in late 2007, the Texas State Board of Education did something rather unusual. They rejected the 3rd edition of [Everyday Math](/Mathematics), despite earlier versions having been used in over 70 districts statewide. The fact that they singled out this one program, while approving 162 other materials, naturally raised eyebrows about the board's actual legal authority. Texas then officially dropped [Everyday Mathematics](/Mathematics), with the official line being that it left public school graduates woefully unprepared for college. A rather damning indictment, if true.

